postcontent:
This one is sold, check out my other listings !

I used good quality mid range priced parts that will work fine together to custom build this rifle. Not too fancy but no crap either. That pretty much sums it up and do not let the technical details bother you, it is from the manufacturer so just in case you are into these details, here you have them...

AR-15 M4 configuration Nato 5.56mm (fires the .223 as well...)

New Frontier lower complete lightweight with lifetime warranty!

PSA CHF 16'' 5.56mm 1:7 M4A1 Profile 
16" Barrel length
5.56 Nato Chamber
1 in 7" twist rate
Extra-thick chrome-lined bore
M4 Feed ramps
F-Marked Front sight post
A2 Flash Hider
Sling Loop
Carbine Hand Guards w/ heat sheilds
Forged upper receiver
T-Marks
M16 style bolt carrier group
Charging handle
Barrel:  A proprietary blend of Hammer forged chrome molly vanadium made by FN that is referred to as "Machine Gun Steel" by virtue of its required use in FN's M249 and M240 weapons.   The hammer forging process work hardens the steel, making it more durable.  In addition, the chrome process for the bore allows for a lining almost twice as thick as a standard M16 for enhanced durability.  Chambered in 5.56 NATO, with a 1/7 twist, M4 barrel extension, and a carbine-length gas system.   The M4A1 profile barrel  is Mil-spec phosphate coated, High Pressure tested and Magnetic Particle inspected.  Barrel is finished off with an F-marked front sight post with sling swivel, standard handguards and an A2 flash hider.
Upper: Forged 7075-T6 A3 AR upper is hard coat anodized black for durability. Featuring T-marks, these upper upper receivers are made for us right here in the USA.
Each upper is assembled to order with US-made parts, and test fired to check gas function.

Unlike the cheaper brand AR-15 this one has a forward assist and shell deflector !

Retail value 850.00 USD

This M4 comes in the A2 flat top pattern. On this flat top I installed a regular carry handle that gives it the A1 appearance but also the freedom to install any other gimmicks on the RIS on top. OR to simply add a scope on the carry handle, too !
I also installed a RIS system free floating hand guard that accepts all kind of attachments from lights to lasers etc.etc. so is prepared for upgrades.
The weight is also below standard which makes it more fun to carry on your property or range than the regular weight rifles.
I did test fire this rifle here on my property with different ammo using a 20 round magazine that it will come with. No problems at all ! Very happy with the result. About 50 rounds fired all in all. In a Zombie attack, I would trust this rifle.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Franchi 12 gauge Black Magic
postcontent:
Very nice gun, awesome condition.  the stock had a hairline crack in it, had it stripped and fixed, then refinished.  very nice dark wood stain.  it is gas operated semi auto, very easy to take apart and clean.  gold trigger and trim in great condition. 3" chamber, chrome-moly ribbed barrel.  i just have zero use for it as i am not a shotgun guy by any means. 

you cannot find this gun for sale anymore.  there are a coupe fake auction sites out there that say they have sold these for 366.00 but that is 100% not true and they say that about everygun to lure you to the site.  please base prices off of gunbroker.com  that is the only acurate site if you must base off of an auction site.  these sold for $600+ when they were in stores.

the reason they are not sold anymore... gas operated shotguns will cycle through any shell clean.  most semi auto shotguns are inertia based and will only cycle through when enough inertia is made from the load.  gas ones cost too much to make when people didnt know the difference between gas and inertia.  so they decided to make 12g models that werent gas and discontinued the gas ones.  still easy to find parts for online, not that you'll need them.

text REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Parker VH 12 gauge.
location: New Jersey, New Jersey, United States
postcontent: This is a very interesting shotgun from the Parker company manufactured in 1916. Parker collectors will enjoy this story as proved by the letter from Parker Gun Collectors Assoc. The gentleman ordered a Parker 10 gauge Damascus gun in 1911. He returned it to Parker and had 12 gauge steel barrels fitted in 1915. He returned it again to Parker in 1916 to have a new receiver and stock fitted to his existing barrels thus a 10 gauge frame with 12 gauge barrels. The gun was made to his specifications with a 4 1/9" grip,triggers 1 5/16" apart, trigger pull 4.5 pounds,LOP 13/3/4" drop 1 7/8 X 2 1/2" and no safety.
